nib.text:
Police are investigating an apparent shooting near George Floyd Square Tuesday morning that had protesters and journalists taking cover.

According to the Minneapolis Police Department, at 10:09 a.m., police responded to the 3800 block of Elliott Avenue south for a report of the sound of shots fired.

A short time later, an individual was dropped off at Abbott Northwestern Hospital suffering from a gunshot wound.

The victim was transported to Hennepin County Medical Center for treatment and is believed to have suffered a non-life-threatening injury.

Journalists who were at the square for the one-year anniversary of George Floyd’s death reported that  bystanders ducked for cover and sheltered in place following the sound of dozens of gunshots.

AP reporter Philip Crowther, who was broadcasting live as the apparent shots rang out, said that reporters counted 30 gunshots. He also reported seeing a window that was apparently broken in the shooting.

Crowther reported that no one at the scene appeared to be injured in the incident.

Molly Hennessy-Fiske, a journalist for the Los Angeles Times, also confirmed hearing the shots, reporting that they came in three volleys.

"People couldn’t tell if it was fireworks at first. It was right in the square," she tweeted.

Multiple 911 callers reported a dark-colored SUV that was seen fleeing the area.

At around 10:30 a.m., officers were investigating the 3800 block of Elliot Ave, where a 911 caller reported blood on a garage.

The incident remains under investigation.
